'''Nericell''' is a system which uses [[smartphone]]s for monitoring [[traffic]] data.<ref name="Mohan2008">{{cite conference |authors=Mohan, Prashanth, Venkata N. Padmanabhan, and Ramachandran Ramjee |title=Nericell: rich monitoring of road and traffic conditions using mobile smartphones |conference=Proceedings of the 6th ACM conference on Embedded network sensor systems |year=2008 |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1460444}}</ref> Nericell performs rich sensing by piggybacking on smartphones that users carry. It uses the [[accelerometer]], [[radio]], [[GPS]],  and [[microphone]] sensors found in these phones to detect [[pothole]]s, bumps, [[brake|braking]], and honking. Nericell addresses several issues, including virtually reorienting the accelerometer on a phone that is in an arbitrary orientation, and performing honk detection and localization in an [[Efficient energy use|energy efficient]] manner.{{r|Mohan2008}}

